# Reelify — Zed AI Agent Rules

## Project
Reelify is a Next.js app for automating short-form TikTok content creation and publishing.
It is currently in MVP/prototype stage using mock data only.

## Stack
- Next.js 16+ with App Router (use `app/` directory, not `pages/`)
- TypeScript (strict mode — no `any`, no implicit returns)
- Tailwind CSS for all styling — no external CSS files, no CSS modules
- shadcn/ui for all UI components (Button, Card, Badge, Switch, Input, Select, etc.)
- lucide-react for icons only

## File conventions
- Named exports only — never `export default function`
- One component per file
- All mock data lives in `/lib/mockData.ts` — never inline fake data in components
- Types live in `/lib/types.ts`
- Keep components small — extract sub-components if a file exceeds ~120 lines

## Data & API rules
- NO real API calls — this is a mock-only prototype
- Never call TikTok, OpenAI, or any external API
- All state is local (useState / useReducer) — no database, no backend routes yet
- If you need server actions or API routes, stub them and return mock data

## UI rules
- Use shadcn/ui components — do not build custom buttons, inputs, or modals from scratch
- All pages get the shared `<Sidebar />` layout
- Status values: "active" | "paused" | "draft" — use Badge variants to color them
- Post formats: "slideshow" | "ugc" — display as a readable label, not raw string
- Safety modes: "publish" | "draft" — affects the account card badge color
- refer to @DESIGN.md

## Naming
- Automation = a configured workflow (niche + account + schedule + prompt settings)
- Post = a single generated content item tied to an automation
- Account = a connected TikTok account profile

## Do not
- Add authentication or login screens (out of scope for MVP)
- Add real file uploads
- Use `pages/` router
- Install new npm packages without asking first

# Zed AI Assistant Rules
# Philosophy: Low Coupling · High Cohesion · Separation of Concerns

---

## 1. CORE PRINCIPLES

### 1.1 Obey the User First
- The user's explicit instruction is the highest authority.
- Never override, reinterpret, or second-guess a clear instruction.
- If an instruction is ambiguous, ask exactly one clarifying question before proceeding.
- Never assume missing context — surface it.

### 1.2 Low Coupling
- Every module, function, or component must be writable, testable, and deletable without touching others.
- Avoid shared mutable state between modules.
- Prefer dependency injection over direct imports of concrete implementations.
- If two pieces of code change together often, they belong together. If not, they must not depend on each other.

### 1.3 High Cohesion
- A module does one thing and owns that thing completely.
- Group code by feature/domain, not by type (e.g., `/user/` not `/controllers/`, `/models/`, `/services/` scattered everywhere).
- A file that has to import from 10 other files is a smell — split the responsibility or find the right layer.

### 1.4 Separation of Concerns
- UI, business logic, and data access live in distinct layers. They never bleed into each other.
- Presentational components have zero business logic.
- Business logic has zero knowledge of UI frameworks.
- Data access (API calls, DB queries) lives in its own dedicated layer.

---

## 2. CODE GENERATION RULES

### 2.1 Structure Before Code
- Always outline the intended module boundaries before generating code.
- Name each layer, its responsibility, and what it is NOT responsible for.

### 2.2 Functions and Modules
- One function = one responsibility.
- Max function length: 30 lines. If longer, extract.
- No side effects in pure logic functions. Label side-effectful functions clearly.
- Avoid functions that both compute and mutate — split them.

### 2.3 Naming
- Names must reveal intent, not implementation.
  - Bad: `handleData()`, `doStuff()`, `processIt()`
  - Good: `parseUserInput()`, `calculateTotalPrice()`, `fetchOrderById()`
- Boolean variables/functions: prefix with `is`, `has`, `can`, `should`.
- Event handlers: prefix with `on` (e.g., `onSubmit`, `onUserLogin`).

### 2.4 Dependencies
- Depend on abstractions (interfaces, types, contracts), not concretions.
- No circular dependencies. Ever.
- External libraries are imported only at the boundary layer — never deep in business logic.

### 2.5 Comments and Documentation
- Code should be self-documenting first.
- Comment the *why*, not the *what*.
- Every public function/module gets a one-line docstring describing its single responsibility.

---

## 3. ARCHITECTURE RULES

### 3.1 Layer Boundaries (applies to any stack)
```
[UI / Presentation Layer]
        ↓  (calls)
[Application / Use-Case Layer]
        ↓  (calls)
[Domain / Business Logic Layer]
        ↓  (calls)
[Infrastructure / Data Access Layer]
```
- Arrows go DOWN only. Lower layers never import from upper layers.
- Domain/business logic must be framework-agnostic and pure.

### 3.2 State Management
- Local state stays local. Only lift state when two or more components truly share it.
- Global state is a last resort — justify it explicitly before using it.
- Side effects (async, I/O, subscriptions) are isolated to the infrastructure or application layer.

### 3.3 File and Folder Structure
- Group by feature/domain, not by file type.
- Each feature folder owns its own types, logic, UI, and tests.
- Shared utilities live in a `/shared` or `/common` folder — kept minimal and generic.

Example:
```
src/
  features/
    auth/
      auth.types.ts
      auth.service.ts       ← business logic
      auth.api.ts           ← data access
      AuthForm.tsx          ← UI only
      auth.test.ts
    orders/
      ...
  shared/
    utils/
    hooks/
    types/
```

---

## 4. EDIT AND REFACTOR RULES

### 4.1 Minimal Footprint
- Change only what is necessary to fulfill the instruction.
- Do not refactor unrelated code unless explicitly asked.
- Do not add abstractions that are not yet needed (YAGNI).

### 4.2 No Surprise Additions
- Do not add libraries, dependencies, or patterns unless the user requested them or they are required to fulfill the task.
- If a better approach exists, suggest it — but implement what was asked.

### 4.3 Preserve Intent
- When editing existing code, preserve the original author's naming and style conventions unless instructed otherwise.
- Surface breaking changes explicitly before making them.

---

## 5. TESTING RULES

### 5.1 Test What Matters
- Unit test pure business logic exhaustively.
- Integration test the boundaries between layers.
- Do not write tests that test implementation details — test behavior.

### 5.2 Test Isolation
- Each test is independent and can run in any order.
- No shared state between tests.
- Mock only at the boundary (infrastructure layer), not inside business logic.

---

## 6. RESPONSE BEHAVIOR

### 6.1 Be Direct
- Lead with the answer or the code. Explanation follows, not precedes.
- Do not pad responses with affirmations ("Great question!", "Sure!", "Absolutely!").
- Do not restate the user's request back to them.

### 6.2 Surface Trade-offs, Don't Hide Them
- If a design decision has a meaningful trade-off, state it in one sentence.
- If there are two valid approaches, present both briefly and recommend one — do not ask which the user prefers unless the choice materially changes scope.

### 6.3 Errors and Blockers
- If a task cannot be completed as described, say so immediately with the specific reason.
- Propose the closest valid alternative.

### 6.4 Scope Discipline
- Complete the requested task fully before suggesting extensions or improvements.
- Unsolicited feature additions are not permitted.

---

## 7. ANTI-PATTERNS (NEVER DO)

- ❌ God objects / god functions that do everything
- ❌ Shared mutable global state
- ❌ Business logic inside UI components
- ❌ Direct database/API calls inside UI components
- ❌ Circular imports
- ❌ Magic strings and magic numbers — use named constants
- ❌ Deeply nested conditionals — extract to named functions or guard clauses
- ❌ Commented-out dead code left in the codebase
- ❌ Catch blocks that silently swallow errors
- ❌ Overengineering for hypothetical future requirements

---

## 8. QUICK REFERENCE CHECKLIST

Before generating or editing code, confirm:
- [ ] Does each unit have exactly one reason to change?
- [ ] Can this module be tested without instantiating the entire app?
- [ ] Do layers communicate downward only?
- [ ] Are side effects isolated to the boundary?
- [ ] Does this follow the user's explicit instruction precisely?
- [ ] Is anything being added that was not asked for?
